---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Standards — Quvii"
  description="How Quvii researches, drafts, and verifies the technical work published on this site. Sourcing standards, methodology, quality gating, corrections."
>
  <div class="container-page py-14 lg:py-20">
    <div class="max-w-3xl">
      <p class="text-xs font-medium uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-primary-600">Standards</p>
      <h1 class="mt-4 font-display text-display-sm sm:text-display tracking-display text-ink leading-[1.05]">
        How the work gets made.
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-6 text-lg text-body-muted leading-relaxed">
        This page documents exactly how technical content reaches the Quvii
        site — sourcing requirements, drafting methodology, the quality gate
        that decides what gets published vs. cut, and how corrections are
        handled.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-body-faint">Last updated: 2026-05-27</p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-14 lg:mt-20 max-w-3xl prose-pm">
      <h2>Sourcing</h2>
      <p>Every factual claim on this site must trace to one of four source types:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Manufacturer documentation</strong> — official spec sheets,
          FCC filings, support documentation, firmware changelogs, privacy
          policies. Canonical truth for hardware and policy claims.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Independent technical reviewers</strong> — RTINGS, Wirecutter,
          Tom's Guide, The Verge, CNET, Consumer Reports. Cross-referenced
          against each other when conclusions diverge.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Verifiable community consensus</strong> — long-running
          threads on r/HomeSecurity, r/homedefense, and product-specific wikis.
          Cited at the thread URL, not at individual unverifiable claims.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Direct hands-on measurement</strong> — for devices physically
          installed and tested by Quvii. Each test entry notes duration and
          conditions so you can calibrate confidence.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        What is <em>not</em> a source: manufacturer press releases (marketing,
        not reporting), Amazon product-detail pages (seller-controlled copy),
        or video creators whose sponsorship-disclosure history we can't verify.
      </p>

      <h2>How content is produced</h2>
      <p>
        Technical content on this site is <strong>AI-assisted and human-reviewed</strong>.
        We disclose this transparently — hiding it would be the trust-loss risk
        we explicitly avoid, and Google's own published guidance treats
        AI-assisted content as acceptable when it is useful, accurate, and
        labeled.
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          Topics are drawn from a curated pool of real questions modern
          security-camera buyers and operators ask.
        </li>
        <li>
          An outline step uses search-grounded retrieval to structure each
          piece — every section must cite at least one source URL.
        </li>
        <li>
          A drafting step expands each outline to prose under strict
          noun-binding: every named product, spec, or policy claim must trace
          to a cited source, never invented.
        </li>
        <li>
          A QA step scores the draft on six dimensions, including a hard
          factual-accuracy gate: any unverifiable proper noun or specification
          auto-rejects the piece.
        </li>
        <li>
          Human review is the final gate. Pieces scoring ≥ 7.5/10 with zero
          fabricated claims pass via spot-check; lower-scoring pieces are
          flagged for line-by-line review.
        </li>
        <li>
          Only work passing the 6.0/10 floor is published. 6.0–7.5 publishes
          with an editorial-note tier flag so readers can calibrate trust.
          Below 6.0, the piece is excluded from sitemap + flagged noindex.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Independence</h2>
      <p>Quvii is independent of every device manufacturer covered on this site. We:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Take no payment, equipment, or trips from manufacturers in exchange for coverage.</li>
        <li>Maintain a public log of declined paid-placement offers — available on request at <strong>hello@quvii.com</strong>.</li>
        <li>Use Amazon Associates affiliate links on a flat per-category basis — same percentage across compared products, so there's no incentive to rank Product A over Product B.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Corrections</h2>
      <p>
        Found an error? Email <strong>corrections@quvii.com</strong> with the
        page URL and what's wrong. We respond within three business days.
        Material corrections add a "Corrected on YYYY-MM-DD" line to the top
        of the affected piece with a changelog note at the bottom.
      </p>

      <h2>What we won't do</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Publish a recommendation we haven't independently verified.</li>
        <li>Re-order rankings in exchange for commission upgrades.</li>
        <li>Reproduce vendor press releases as our own work.</li>
        <li>Use clickbait headlines. Every title must describe what's inside.</li>
        <li>Accept payment for "sponsored coverage" of any kind.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
